\hypertarget{week-6-sliding-mode-control}{%
\section{Week 6: Sliding Mode Control}\label{week-6-sliding-mode-control}}

Variable Structure Control --- Robust Tracking Under Uncertainty

M.Sc. Control for Robots • AY 2025--26\\
Week 6 of 12 • Lecture + Hands-on MATLAB Lab

\hypertarget{week-7-recall-backstepping-control-exam-practice}{%
\subsection{Week 7 Recall: Backstepping Control --- Exam Practice}\label{week-7-recall-backstepping-control-exam-practice}}

\hypertarget{question-1-scalar-strict-feedback-system}{%
\subsubsection{Question 1 --- Scalar Strict-Feedback System}\label{question-1-scalar-strict-feedback-system}}

Consider the strict-feedback system:

\[
                \dot{x}_1 = x_2 + x_1^2, \qquad \dot{x}_2 = u.
            \]

\hypertarget{step-1-virtual-control-design}{%
\paragraph{Step 1 --- Virtual Control Design}\label{step-1-virtual-control-design}}

Define the first error variable:

\[ z_1 = x_1. \]

Choose the first Lyapunov function:

\[ V_1 = \tfrac{1}{2}\,z_1^2. \]

Its time derivative is:

\[
                \dot{V}_1 = z_1\,\dot{z}_1 = z_1\bigl(x_2 + x_1^2\bigr).
            \]

We want \(\dot{V}_1 = -k_1 z_1^2\) when \(x_2\) equals a virtual control \(\alpha_1(x_1)\). Setting

\[
                z_1\bigl(\alpha_1 + x_1^2\bigr) = -k_1 z_1^2
                \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
                \alpha_1(x_1) = -k_1 x_1 - x_1^2.
            \]

\hypertarget{step-2-actual-control-design}{%
\paragraph{Step 2 --- Actual Control Design}\label{step-2-actual-control-design}}

Define the second error variable:

\[ z_2 = x_2 - \alpha_1(x_1). \]

Note that \(x_2 = z_2 + \alpha_1\), so

\[
                \dot{V}_1 = z_1(z_2 + \alpha_1 + x_1^2) = -k_1 z_1^2 + z_1 z_2.
            \]

Augment the Lyapunov function:

\[ V_2 = V_1 + \tfrac{1}{2}\,z_2^2 = \tfrac{1}{2}z_1^2 + \tfrac{1}{2}z_2^2. \]

Differentiate \(z_2\):

\[
                \dot{z}_2 = \dot{x}_2 - \dot{\alpha}_1
                = u - \frac{\partial \alpha_1}{\partial x_1}\dot{x}_1
                = u - (-k_1 - 2x_1)(x_2 + x_1^2).
            \]

Compute \(\dot{V}_2\):

\[
                \dot{V}_2 = -k_1 z_1^2 + z_1 z_2 + z_2\dot{z}_2
                = -k_1 z_1^2 + z_2\bigl[z_1 + u + (k_1 + 2x_1)(x_2 + x_1^2)\bigr].
            \]

To obtain \(\dot{V}_2 = -k_1 z_1^2 - k_2 z_2^2\), choose:

\[
                    u = -z_1 - k_2 z_2 - (k_1 + 2x_1)(x_2 + x_1^2).
                \]

This yields \(\dot{V}_2 = -k_1 z_1^2 - k_2 z_2^2 \le 0\), guaranteeing global asymptotic stability.

\hypertarget{question-2-2-dof-manipulator-backstepping}{%
\subsubsection{Question 2 --- 2-DOF Manipulator Backstepping}\label{question-2-2-dof-manipulator-backstepping}}

Given the manipulator dynamics \(M(q)\ddot{q} + C(q,\dot{q})\dot{q} + G(q) = \tau\), define:

\[
                z_1 = q - q_d, \qquad
                \alpha_1 = \dot{q}_d - K_1 z_1, \qquad
                z_2 = \dot{q} - \alpha_1.
            \]

Choose the composite Lyapunov function:

\[
                V_2 = \tfrac{1}{2}\,z_1^T z_1 + \tfrac{1}{2}\,z_2^T M(q)\,z_2.
            \]

Differentiate:

\[
                \dot{V}_2 = z_1^T \dot{z}_1 + z_2^T M(q)\dot{z}_2 + \tfrac{1}{2}\,z_2^T \dot{M}(q)\,z_2.
            \]

Since \(\dot{z}_1 = \dot{q} - \dot{q}_d = z_2 + \alpha_1 - \dot{q}_d = z_2 - K_1 z_1\), we get:

\[
                z_1^T \dot{z}_1 = -z_1^T K_1 z_1 + z_1^T z_2.
            \]

For the second term, note \(\dot{z}_2 = \ddot{q} - \dot{\alpha}_1\), and from the dynamics \(M\ddot{q} = \tau - C\dot{q} - G\), so:

\[
                M\dot{z}_2 = \tau - C\dot{q} - G - M\dot{\alpha}_1.
            \]

Using the skew-symmetry property \(z_2^T(\dot{M} - 2C)z_2 = 0\):

\[
                \dot{V}_2 = -z_1^T K_1 z_1 + z_1^T z_2 + z_2^T\bigl[\tau - C\dot{q} - G - M\dot{\alpha}_1 + C z_2\bigr].
            \]

Simplifying \(-C\dot{q} + Cz_2 = -C(\dot{q} - z_2) = -C\alpha_1\), so:

\[
                \dot{V}_2 = -z_1^T K_1 z_1 + z_2^T\bigl[z_1 + \tau - C\alpha_1 - G - M\dot{\alpha}_1\bigr].
            \]

Choose the backstepping torque:

\[
                    \tau = M\dot{\alpha}_1 + C\alpha_1 + G - z_1 - K_2 z_2
                \]

which yields \(\dot{V}_2 = -z_1^T K_1 z_1 - z_2^T K_2 z_2 \le 0\).

\hypertarget{learning-outcomes}{%
\subsection{Learning Outcomes}\label{learning-outcomes}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Understand the two phases of sliding mode control: the \textbf{reaching phase} (driving the state to the sliding surface) and the \textbf{sliding phase} (reduced-order dynamics on \(s=0\)); derive the \textbf{equivalent control}.
\item
  Design \textbf{sliding surfaces} for second-order systems and multi-DOF robots: choose surface parameters \(\lambda\) or \(\Lambda\) to assign desired closed-loop error dynamics.
\item
  Derive complete SMC laws for three robotic platforms: \textbf{manipulator}, \textbf{mobile robot}, and \textbf{quadrotor drone}.
\item
  Analyse and mitigate the \textbf{chattering problem} using the boundary layer approach (\(\operatorname{sat}(s/\varphi)\)), and the \textbf{super-twisting algorithm}.
\item
  Implement SMC in \textbf{MATLAB/Simulink}, inject disturbances, and compare performance against computed torque, robust control, and backstepping.
\end{itemize}

